up|52|NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|First, the bidding. Had East chosen to pass 1@H which is probably what I would have done, although 2C is ok, then I would bid 1N. You might think that the auction 1D-1H-P-P-1N says opener has 12-14. Many players do. But that is not correct. Partner passed, so is likely to have very little. Therefore, bidding 1N with 12-14 is incorrect and very dangerous. Freely bidding 1N after a passing partner shows a very strong hand, 18+.|
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If I had 15-17 I would have opened 1N. Therefore, 1N in 1D-1H-P-P-1N must show even a stronger hand. If you rebid 1N after partner has passed, you must have 18+.|
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to the play. East made a nice play at trick 1. Sandy should have a doubleton when she leads the 8. When you lead partner's suit and have not supported it, you lead ^*Bcount^*N. With @C8xx Sandy should lead low. Therefore, Sandy should have a doubleton (or possibly a singleton). This is a good illustration of why you must lead ^*Bcount^*N when you have not supported partner.|
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Anyway, East can figure out I have @CK9 in my hand, and wants to save the @CA to capture an honor.|
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|At trick 6, after drawing trump and throwing East in, East made a slight error. She led a low @S4. @S10 is better because a low spade confused Sandy who won the trick and played @SK. Had East led the 10, then Sandy would know that I have the @SQJ. |
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But since East led low, Sandy assumed East had an honor, and decided to cash the @SAK rather than leading away from her @HK. That gave me my 8th trick. The moral of this hand is, it is easy to misdefend, even experts do it a lot. So sometimes, in what appears to be a hopeless contract, throw in the defense and hope they give you a trick.|
